<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900917-0107</DOCNO><DOCID>900917-0107.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   A Touch of Glamour   Gets Them Hooked</HL><DATE>09/17/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15</SO><IN>LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)BEVERAGES (BVG)DISTILLERS AND BREWERS, MAKERS OF ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES (DST)</IN><LP>   Your Aug. 10 article &quot;Plaintiffs Strike a Blow forShifting Blame for Accidents Caused by Their Own Acts&quot; wasinteresting and informative.   For several years legislative efforts have been made in anumber of states (including my state of Wisconsin) to enactso-called &quot;Common Knowledge Defense&quot; laws. Reportedly, thoseinitiatives enjoyed the financial backing of the alcohol andtobacco industries.</LP><TEXT>   Simply stated: If it's &quot;common knowledge&quot; that using aproduct can be harmful and a person uses it anyway, theperson is negligent for his or her own safety and is barredfrom suing the manufacturer. Without identifying it, the&quot;Shifting Blame&quot; article covered the subject quite well.   However, missing from it was the added element of whetherthe product is addictive. In the case of alcohol and tobacco,how important is the fact that children in this country --from a very early age -- are subjected to daily&quot;glamorization&quot; of harmful products in print, billboard,scoreboard and electronic media ads. Is a sub-teenage child,&quot;hooked&quot; on an addictive substance, responsible for possibleconsequences that may be 20, 30 or 40 years in the future?Where does the &quot;blame&quot; lie?   Thomas Kent Guelzow   President-elect   Wisconsin Academy of Trial Lawyers   Madison, Wis.</TEXT></DOC>